<div style="background:linear-gradient(150deg, #CC7F3BCC, #D2691ECC, #B87333CC);  border: 4px solid black; border-radius:100px; padding:8px;box-shadow:0 2px 6px rgba(0,0,255,0.5), inset 0 1px rgba(60,70,240,0.3), inset 0 10px rgba(200,200,255,,0.2), inset 0 10px 20px rgba(255,255,255,0.25), inset 0 -15px 30px rgba(255,255,255,0.3);margin:10px;color:black; font-family:Protest Guerrilla; font-size: 24px;"><center><u>'''General Description'''</u></center></div>
{{Blurimage|caption=An image of '''Level 245'''.|file=Webpssuck.png|width=330px}}
{{Blurimage|caption=An image of a sparser area of '''Level 245'''.|file=Webpssuckoncemore.png|width=330px}}
'''Level 245''', colloquially referred to as '''"Soviet Languor"''' or '''"The City That Always Sleeps,"''' is an expansive, arid plain with a Soviet-era town sporting khrushchevkas<ref>[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khrushchevka Khrushchevkas] are Soviet-style apartment housing commonly referred to as "commie blocks" in popular culture.</ref>, sparse greenery, wide empty roads, overgrown dirt paths, winding creeks, and old cottages throughout its expanses. The level's buildings have signs of decay, with broken windows, chipped paneling, and cracked concrete. The level has no day/night cycle and always locks to daytime, with no discernible celestial object lighting up the level. The level's temperature is relatively low, averaging at 0.8°C (33.4°F).

Several different types of clouds blanket '''Level 245'''. The most common clouds are cumulus clouds, which are regular fluffy clouds. Occasionally, these can accumulate into nimbostratus clouds, which are large enough to cause precipitation in the form of snow. During this, the natural illumination of the level is weaker, and snow accumulates in heaps throughout the level. The level's temperatures are very frigid during snow, where it can inflict hypothermia on wanderers.

The ground comprises hard bedrock piled with a thin layer of topsoil where vegetation thrives. The bedrock possesses near-indestructible properties, and most destructive forces leave minor dents on the material. The basements and foundations of the buildings integrate themselves within the bedrock. Rarely, one may come across large fissures penetrating the bedrock, appearing pitch black and extending to unknown depths. Some parts of the topsoil in some areas are instead permafrost, primarily due to the frigid snowfalls.

The interior of the khrushchevkas consists of oddly segmented rooms displaying abandonment and dilapidation. One may find scattered debris, rotten foodstuffs, termite infestations, and dead insects throughout the buildings. Mold and dangerous varieties of [[Object 10|Backshrooms]] line the interiors of the buildings. Graffiti rampantly plagues the buildings - inside and out - displaying incoherent messages using the Cyrillic alphabet. The interiors of most bedrooms within the khrushchevkas are less ravaged than the rest of the building and contain beneficial supplies such as MREs and [[Object 1|Almond Water]].

{{Blurimage|caption=An image of the interior of a khrushchevka.|file=245inside.jpg|width=255px|align=left}}
Within the walls of the apartment complexes, a pungent durian-like smell inundates the air. The range of this smell extends outside the building at 15 meters (50 feet). There is no clear origin point for the odor since if one tries to trace its origin point, it will "shift" to another location until one retraces it. Additionally, a petrichor-like<ref>Petrichor describes the scent one would conventionally characterize as "the scent of earth after rainfall."</ref> smell permeates the outdoor sections of '''Level 245''', regardless of the weather. The outdoor scent gives wanderers a slight sense of peacefulness and euphoria. The scent's origin depends, as it usually originates from the ground, although it becomes much stronger as one slowly approaches a plant covered with dew.

One may find drugstores sparsely scattered throughout the level. These drugstores appear badly ransacked, as aisles appear toppled, rubbish is littered all over the store, and an unidentifiable liquid seeps from the trash and floor. The stores are lit up by weak ceiling lights, producing no heat and occasionally flicking. Despite this, it is unadvised to touch the lights, as the lights and any nearby wiring can easily electrocute a wanderer. On the cashiers, one may find a 1970s computer displaying images of other levels of the Backrooms.

Cars commonly dot the streets of '''Level 245'''. These cars are parked on roadsides, and while they can be opened without a key, one cannot start the engine. The car models resemble cars from the Russian Federation, a country in [[the Frontrooms]]. The cars's production years range from the late 40's to the early 90's, implying that these cars were produced during the Soviet era, although one may rarely spot cars from other, newer eras. Occasionally, one may find a supply crate on the car's trunk or a [[Object 2|Level Key]] on the passenger seat glovebox.
